\subsection{Ablation Study: Component Contribution Analysis}
\label{subsec:ablation}
To validate architectural choices, we conduct ablation experiments on synthetic benchmarks. Table~\ref{tab:ablation} shows system performance with key components removed.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Ablation study: removing components degrades performance differentially. Full Aetherion balances all three metrics.}
\label{tab:ablation}
\begin{tabular}{|l|c|c|c|}
\hline
\textbf{Model Variant} & \textbf{Efficiency $\eta$} & \textbf{Alignment Score} & \textbf{Integration $\Phi$} \\
\hline
Aetherion-Full & 4.8 & 0.96 & 3.3 \\
\hline
$-$ Ethos Core & 5.0 & 0.45 & 3.1 \\
$-$ Energy Loop & 4.3 & 0.82 & 2.8 \\
$-$ Evolution Engine & 3.9 & 0.91 & 2.4 \\
$-$ Self-Model Layer & 4.1 & 0.73 & 1.9 \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\noindent\textbf{Observations:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item Removing the \emph{Ethos Core} increases efficiency (fewer constraints) but catastrophically reduces alignment.
  \item Removing the \emph{Energy Loop} decreases efficiency and integration due to unregulated activation.
  \item Removing the \emph{Evolution Engine} prevents architectural adaptation, reducing all metrics.
  \item Removing the \emph{Self-Model Layer} impairs introspection, degrading alignment and integration significantly.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Scaling Law Validation}
We validate the predicted scaling relationships from UTEI (Eqs.~\ref{eq:scaling-q}--\ref{eq:scaling-d}) through controlled simulation.

